body:
### Version

Yosys 0.53+15 (git sha1 690081810, clang++ 18.1.8 -fPIC -O3)

### On which OS did this happen?

Linux

### Reproduction Steps

This design is for the ECP5, it uses ECP5 memory primitives so it's best you use an ECP5 if you want to reproduce this, even better if it's an ECP5 Evaluation Board since that's what I'm using and what the C tools I wrote work with.

1. Download the zip archive and run `make load` to load the design to the FPGA. If it doesn't it's either because openFPGALoader is not installed, the toolchain (nextpnr-ecp5, yosys and ecppack) is not installed, or the current user doesn't have USB permission to the FTDI bridge. Otherwise it should load fine and the LEDs will power off.
2. Install libftdi and a riscv32 assembler (I use `riscv32-elf-as` in the Makefile), then run `make test` to send and execute the code, or `make test_edit` to edit the assembly before sending it (this command opens up the `hx` test editor so change it in the Makefile you don't have it installed). If this fails it's most likely a USB permission issue or a kernel module not letting libftdi access the FTDI bridge, if it's the former simply run `make test` with higher privileges, if it's the latter run `sudo rmmod ftdi_sio` and retry, that's usually the kernel module you need to kill.
3. Send code with a bge instruction that has an odd register as rs1, and then try again with an even register. You will see that in the latter case it works as expected, and in the former it never takes the branch.

[v1_draft.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/23295852/v1_draft.zip)

### Expected Behavior

It should work on both cases.

### Actual Behavior

It only works as expected with rs1 as an even register, otherwise the branch is never taken.

**Extra info:**
Hello,
I've been using yosys+nextpnr to work on a RISCV CPU design and I'm currently having an issue that seems very likely to be miss wiring or faulty synthesis coming from the toolchain.
The CPU has the necessary logic to execute all branch instructions from the RV32I base instruction set, however, `bge` and `bgeu` are only working as expected whenever `rs1` is an even register, such as x2, if it's and odd register, it never takes the branch. 
I've checked my HDL over and over and can't find any obvious bug. The most relevant files to this bug are `src/fsm.v` and `src/branch_dec.v` although that last file is almost certainly not the root of the issue and I know this by experimenting with the state machine: if you make the state machine on the branch state go to a useless state in which it remains stuck only if the `branch` signal from branch_dec.v is asserted, it will indeed only get stuck whenever it should branch, regardless of whether rs1 is even or not. So it's most likely something the synthesis or wiring of the `pc_we` and `pc_sel` signals from fsm.v making them somehow dependent on bit 16 of the instruction (instr[15]). Here's a snippet from the state machine, particularly the branch state and the default values of the control signals. Of course I've also send the zip with the entire code-base. Many thanks.
```
// from fsm.v
// ...
 always @* begin
    cede=0;
    instr_we=0;
    rf_we=0;
    pc_we=0;
    rs1_we=0;
    rs2_we=0;
    alu_we=0;
    prev_pc_we=0;
    mem_op=2'b00;
    //
    alu_op=2'bxx;
    a_sel=2'bxx;
    b_sel=2'bxx;
    wd_sel=3'bxxx;
    pc_sel=2'bxx;
    mem_ad_sel=1'bx;
    case (cpu_state)
    // ...
    S_BRANCH:begin // branch instructions, compute rs1-rs2 and branch (write alu_reg to pc) if a branch signal from another component in the control unit is asserted (said component should receive the instruction and alu flags as inputs),
        if (branch) begin
          pc_sel=2'b1x; // alu_reg
          pc_we=1;
        end
        else pc_we=0;
        a_sel=0;
        b_sel=0;
        alu_op=2'b1x;
      end
    // ...
    default:;
end

```

